<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[264,1323,1431,1657]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
COMMENTS. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashby" authorityYear="1915" box="[494,629,1471,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="woglumi">
<emphasis box="[494,629,1471,1496]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. woglumi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is often known as the citrus blackfly because of the black puparia, combined with the dark bodies and dusky wings of the adults. Although this species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[596,694,1551,1577]" name="Jamaica" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
, it is almost certain that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashby" authorityYear="1915" box="[983,1118,1551,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Aleurocanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="woglumi">
<emphasis box="[983,1118,1551,1576]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. woglumi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a native of the Oriental or Austro­oriental Region, and it is currently the only member of this important genus known in Central America.
</paragraph>
